.TH xdiff 3
.XI xdiff - "External graphical file difference" command|shell
.XI %xdiff-com 5 "xdiff command line" variable
.SH NAME
xdiff \- External graphical file difference
.br
%xdiff-com \- Extenal graphical differnce xdiff(1) command line
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.Me "|xdiff"
.B xdiff
"\fIleftVersion\fR"
"\fIrightVersion\fR"
.sp
.Me "|%xdiff-com"
\fC%xdiff-com\fR "\fIstring\fR"
.sp
X-Windows "\fCxdiff -wb %lf %rf\fR" when using \fBxdiff\fR from
.I http://reality.sgiweb.org/rudy/xdiff/
.sp
MS-Windows "\fCbc2.exe %lf %rf /title1=%lt /title2=%rt\fR"
when using \fBBeyond Compare\fR.
.sp
All "\fCmeld %lf -L %lt %rf -L %rt\fR" when using \fBMeld\fR.
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B xdiff
is a macro wrapper that invokes an external graphical file difference utility,
named after the original  X-Windows utility of the same name. The utility will
usually  display  two files side by side and color code the  differences,  the
differences  may then be selected to merge the changes  into a new output file
which may (or may not) overwrite one of the original input files.
.PP
.B xdiff
executes the difference utility
.Hr xdiff 1
command (or equivalent) with the command line set by the
.B %xdiff-com
variable    and   the    user    supplied    files    \fIleftVersion\fR    and
\fIrightVersion\fR. The command line variables are referenced from the 
.B %xdiff-com
as follows:
.IP \fB%lf\fR
The absolute file name of the left-hand file, \fIleftVersion\fR.
.IP \fB%rf\fR
The absolute file name of the right-hand file, \fIrightVersion\fR.
.IP \fB%lt\fR
The title to use for the left-hand file, \fIleftVersion\fR.
.IP \fB%rt\fR
The title to use for the right-hand file, \fIrightVersion\fR.
.LP
The 
.B %xdiff-com
variable  should  include  the  appropriate  command to invoke the  difference
utility and use \fB%\fR place  holders for the  arguments.  \*(mS will fill in
the \fB%\fR arguments with their correct values on invocation. 
.PP
.Hr Meld 1
is a free graphical file compare available on Gnome capable UNIX systems, Windows and macOS, the variable command line may be defined as:
.LP
.RS
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS 0
set-variable %xdiff-com "meld %lf -L %lt %rf -L %rt"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
.RE
Unix environments may use 
.Hr xdiff 1
which is available from 
.BR http://reality.sgiweb.org/rudy/xdiff/ .
The variable command line may be defined as:
.LP
.RS
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS 0
set-variable %xdiff-com "xdiff -wb %lf %rf"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
.RE
The \fB-wb\fR options will ignore while space and trailing blanks.
.ne 5
Microsoft Windows  environments may use something like \fBBeyond  Compare\fR. The variable command line may be defined
as:
.LP
.RS
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS 0
set-variable %xdiff-com "bc2.exe %lf %rf /title1=%lt /title2=%rt"
.CE 
.Me $ehf-scheme
.RE
In this case the \fB%lt\fR  values have been used for the title names for each
of the windows in the utility.
.SH NOTES
\fBxdiff\fR is a macro defined in \fCtools.emf\fR,  inspired by the \s-1UNIX\s0
utility of the same name
.Hr xdiff 1
